727395f-d.title: Queens: Metropolitan Avenue - 70th Avenue
727395f-d.text:
Metropolitan Avenue, north side, west from Sevenntieth Ave-ue
(forrcrly Herrick Aveue),showirg in four views in the foreground
the houuse and outhuildings of J. Vanderveer. In view No. 1 in
the background is seen the home of Gol. Eunt. Vie.s S,3, and 4
shows the store barn of the Vanderveer family which was erected
in 1850. IIn the 1929 Queens Atlas the buildings seen in these
views no longer apbear. For rore data concerning the Vanderveer
house see views located as the north side of Metropolitan Avenue
opposite Seventieth Avenue.
October 1923

727394f-b.title: Queens: Metropolitan Avenue - 70th Avenue
727394f-b.text:
Metropolitan Avenue, north side, opposite Seventieth Avenue
(known also as Ursula Place and Herrick Auerue). This set of
3 views shows the home of Jeronus Vanderveer. John and Walter
Vcrgderveer were the owners in 19E3 while one Weeden was the
occupant. Michael Vanderveer who settled in Newtown in 1810
was born in Flathush in 1777. Pe rarried Martba Vandervoort
of Newtoxn. His son Henry Suvdam was born in 1812 in the old
koose that stood across the road fror his latter residence,
whick was on the w:st side of Trotting Corrse Lane just south
of Metropolitan Avenue. TEe son, Nenry Suydam, married Sarah J.
(Burroumhs) Rapelje in 1807. George W. Vandorveer was born in
the oli family homestead in Newtown in 1842. He rarried in 1848
hary Whitson of that place. Charles Boerur: Vandcrveer (1796.
1879) owned a thirty-six acre farm at Middle Village. His son
'eronus purchased about 1871 a sixty acre one at the same place.
After his fathrs death he, Jeronus, acoufred bia fatkerw farr..
Othr ovners of this house ere E. Randall, 188O7;H. Needen,
1873; and J. Vanderveer, in 1896. Views 2 and 3 are viewed
east and west resectively.
1922
Views 2a:3: Uctober 1923.
Eugene L. Armhroster Collection
